ce:section.ce:para:
Our method was applied to analyze the values of UA in human serum and urine. The main purpose of this study was to evaluate the practicality and accuracy of the sensor. Five serum samples were subjected to UV–vis and fluorescence analysis and compared with the results of the biochemical analyzer. The generally consistent experimental results indicate that the biosensor has superior accuracy. Experiments on the standard addition method were used to further verify its sensing performance. As shown in Table 2
                        , the recovery rate of the ratio fluorescence method was 91.3–103.8 %, and RSD was less than 3.2 %. The recovery rate using UV–vis absorption method was 93.0–107.0 % with RSD did not exceed 2.9 % (Table 3
                        ). The corresponding optical images before and after the addition of UA standard solution were shown in the Fig. S14. The color change was visible to the naked eye, which was consistent with the corresponding linear regression equation. In two urine samples, the recoveries of fluorescence and colorimetric methods based on Fe CDs/Mo SACs nanozymes were 92.0–107.5 % and 106.5–108.5 %, respectively, with RSD less than 2.8 % for different methods. The excellent recoveries and low relative error of the two detection modes indicate that the dual-mode biosensor has good precision and accuracy, and has great potential in practical applications.
